<P>Mrs. Berkeley certainly had that rage from her very early
youth, and it continued with her until &s;he lo&s;t her idol. It
is not yet quite extinct; the flame is out, but the embers
&s;till glow a little.</P>
<P><PB N="dlxxiii" REF="587">
A wonderfully, well-informed, re&s;pected friend, the Lady
of the late Governor <GAP DESC="blank" RESP="OXF" EXTENT="1 word">, being in the Editor's room
(many years ago) mentioned &s;omething in A&s;tronomy that
was new to the Editor; &s;he &s;prang out upon the &s;tair-ca&s;e,
and called out to Mrs. (then Mi&s;s) Frin&s;ham, <Q REND="inline">"<HI>Si&s;ter, &s;i&s;ter,</HI>
come hither this minute, and Mrs. <GAP DESC="blank" RESP="OXF" EXTENT="1 word"> will make
you as wi&s;e as SOLOMON."</Q> Mrs. Frin&s;ham, dre&s;&s;ing
for dinner, &s;aid, <Q REND="inline">"I am without my cloaths."</Q>&mdash;<Q REND="inline">"<HI>Never
mind your cloaths,</HI> but come directly."</Q> The worthy lady
laughed &s;o violently, that it recovered Mrs. Berkeley from
